address-driving instructions:
    LDA (AI, RO, P2DA) //load A from data memory address from program memory
    LDB (BI, RO, P2DA) //load B from data memory address from program memory
    STA (AO, RI, P2DA) //store A in data memory address from program memory
    JMP (PI, RO) //jump to program memory address in data memory
    JC  (PI, RO) //jump to program memory address in data memory if carry
    JZ  (PI, RO) //jump to program memory address in data memory if zero
    JN  (PI, RO) //jump to program memory address in data memory if negative
    CAL (PI, RO, RAI) //jump to program memory address in data memory and save the current address + 1 in RA register
    RET (PI, RAO) //jump to program memory address in RA register

data-moving instructions:
    MAB (AO, BI) //copy A to B
    MAC (AO, HI) //copy A to H
    MAL (AO, LI) //copy A to L
    OUT (HO, LO) //output H&L
    LDAI (AI, P2D) //load A immediately
    LDBI (BI, P2D) //load B immediately

arithmetic & logic instructions:
    ADD (AI, EO, ADD, FI) //A + B = A
    SUB (AI, EO, FI) //A - B = A
    CMP+ (FI, ADD) //update flag register based on addition without overwriting A
    CMP- (FI) //update flag register based on subtraction without overwriting A
    MUL (CI, MUL) //A * B = H&L
    AND (AI, AND) //A AND B = A
    NOT (AI, NOT) //A = !A
    XOR (AI, XOR) //A XOR B = A
    SHR (AI, SHR) //A >> = A

other instructions:
    HLT (HLT) //halt system clock

abbreviations:
    signals:
        AI: register A in
        AO: register A out
        BI: register B in
        HI: register H in
        HO: register H out
        LI: register L in
        LO: register L out    
        RI: data memory in
        RO: data memory out
        PI: program counter in
        RAI: return address register in
        RAO: return address register out
        FI: flag register in
        EO: arithmetic unit out
        P2D: program memory to data bus
        P2DA: program memory to data memory address bus
    
registers:
    4bit registers:
        1.1-flag register
    8bit registers:
        2.1-register A
        2.2-register B
        2.3-register H
        2.4-register L
        2.5-program counter
        2.6-return address register

architecture:
    single cycle Harvard.

notes:
    1-subtraction is active high and every other signal is active low, the arithmetic unit is always subtracting, but we can control when to output that subtraction, when to save its flags, and when to switch to addition.
    2-the CAL instruction does not use the main arithmetic unit to add 1 to the current address to be saved, but rather it uses a private adder with the program counter as its first input and the constant 1 as its second input.
